The paper focuses on modeling and predicting the socio-emotional impact of groups on observers in virtual environments. This involves using data-driven algorithms to classify and map the motion-based entitativity of crowds, which is likely to fall under the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) and Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper involves statistical learning and multi-agent simulation algorithms, which could also fall under the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), Graphics (cs.GR), and Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories.
